12:02.420 --> 12:11.060
It's a great pleasure to be here particularly because that dream that was conceived in Switzerland

12:11.060 --> 12:16.100
between Genève and Luzon is now real.

12:16.100 --> 12:18.940
I mean we are here.

12:18.940 --> 12:28.180
We will spend two days discussing this amazing figure of Abi Warburg.

12:28.180 --> 12:39.420
I think we begin to appreciate how innovative this approach was, perhaps particularly today.

12:39.420 --> 12:51.340
When we are experiencing a new form of dialogue between disciplines that the first site may

12:51.340 --> 12:59.020
look as remote as possible like the study of the brain, the study of art, of culture.

12:59.020 --> 13:09.780
When Vittorio embodies I think in a marvelous way this curiosity and this attempt to bridge

13:09.780 --> 13:20.340
different field of expertise particularly because cognitive neuroscience is very popular.

13:20.340 --> 13:26.340
Every day we read the big headlines in the newspaper, we discover what romantic love

13:26.340 --> 13:33.500
is all about, we discover a tiny little area where beauty sits and the like.

13:33.500 --> 13:44.980
This I would say, outrageously excessive form of reductionism needs to be tempered by an

13:44.980 --> 13:54.860
open dialogue with people that because of the background tend to look at the individual

13:54.860 --> 13:57.140
in a more holistic way.

13:57.140 --> 14:04.300
So we must bring back the brain to where it belongs to the body in the first place but

14:04.300 --> 14:13.620
this brain body complex it makes sense to study it to the extent that even if we move

14:13.620 --> 14:20.140
from a methodological reductionist approach so we are dealing with the nuts and bolts so

14:20.140 --> 14:27.780
to speak of what it means to be human the ultimate goal must be to go back to the holistic

14:27.780 --> 14:36.340
view of human nature and if we want to do that we cannot live out from our investigation,

14:36.340 --> 14:44.860
artistic expression, creativity and how this relates to something which is hidden in our

14:44.860 --> 14:46.220
psychology.

14:46.220 --> 14:55.380
So I think that the chicanelises, neuroscience, the humanities broadly speaking now finally

14:55.380 --> 15:05.140
are in a position to collaborate to this very exciting enterprise of shedding light on who

15:05.140 --> 15:15.280
we are exploiting also this new level of description that cognitive neuroscience and I think a

15:15.280 --> 15:23.380
prominent figure to bless so to speak this enterprise I couldn't imagine a better figure

15:23.380 --> 15:28.380
than Abhi Babu.

15:28.380 --> 15:36.040
So as I was thinking about today's meeting I thought I didn't think of myself as a neuro

15:36.040 --> 15:42.020
esthetician I think of myself as an art historian who makes use of tools that seem to me that

15:42.020 --> 15:49.740
will illuminate the objects of our studies and as many of you know I have long insisted

15:49.740 --> 15:55.380
on the importance of opening one's mind to science and not getting too anxious about

15:55.380 --> 16:00.460
the alleged reductivism of science but as I was thinking about today's symposium I realised

16:00.460 --> 16:07.860
that probably once one was a child and suddenly one is old and probably I may have been in

16:07.860 --> 16:13.660
this audience the first person to have gone to the Warburg Institute.

16:13.660 --> 16:16.940
So I wondered when I could just begin with a little background.

16:16.940 --> 16:22.820
So I arrived in Oxford to do my graduate work in art history at the end of 1969 and Francis

16:22.820 --> 16:29.900
Haskell who had just taken over from another great and extraordinary hermeneute and art

16:29.900 --> 16:36.700
historian Edgar Vinte who was a Warburgian of course was a high British positivist and

16:36.700 --> 16:41.860
he looked at me and he said you can't study here go to the Warburg Institute in London.

16:41.860 --> 16:47.220
So I went to the Warburg Institute so that was at the end of 1969 and as I was reflecting

16:47.220 --> 16:52.740
on the direction of Warburg in studies and the ways in which many of us here including

16:52.740 --> 16:56.800
myself and Vittorio have sort of seen the links between A.B.

16:56.800 --> 17:02.980
Varbog and neuroscience I realised that it wasn't always so because when I got to the

17:02.980 --> 17:09.180
Warburg Institute the emphasis was completely on both Michael Baxondall and Anne Sconbrick

17:09.180 --> 17:12.380
were completely on the Naheleb and Der Antica.

17:12.380 --> 17:17.180
Gombrick had done his own stuff on perception as we all know in art and delusion but the

17:17.180 --> 17:25.020
real Warburgian work at that time and throughout the 1970s and even into the 1980s was really

17:25.020 --> 17:29.260
about iconography and the Naheleb and Der Antica.

17:29.260 --> 17:35.380
So when I wrote the power of images sort of thinking about the other aspect of A.B.

17:35.380 --> 17:41.180
Varbog which has now come to the fore in other words this kind of psychological roots of

17:41.180 --> 17:47.460
human responses to images embodied above all in the whole notion of the pathos formula

17:47.460 --> 17:49.100
the patos formula.

17:49.100 --> 17:54.980
In other words those aspects of art which move us because of the collocation of emotion

17:54.980 --> 17:59.940
and movement in the body and its effects on the bodies of others which of course tied

17:59.940 --> 18:05.380
up eventually with the work of the Mira Neuron group in Parma.

18:05.380 --> 18:12.820
This was really a very late cumber on the Naheleb and of Varbog himself in London.

18:12.820 --> 18:19.020
No one would have thought that the cognitive neuroscience offered any access to the works

18:19.020 --> 18:20.020
of A.B.

18:20.020 --> 18:21.020
Varbog.

18:21.020 --> 18:24.300
So actually this is all a late development.

18:24.300 --> 18:29.860
And it was always there in Varbog the notion of the emotional consequences of moving drapery

18:29.860 --> 18:31.940
and dancing bodies and so on.

18:31.940 --> 18:36.100
But nobody until fairly recently, I mean we have lots of people here, Chris Wood has

18:36.100 --> 18:41.660
written eloquently about it, Chris Johnson also.

18:41.660 --> 18:50.100
But for a long time the original conception, the rarely original aspect of Warburg's contribution

18:50.100 --> 19:01.580
was relegated to this more positivist decoding of the great iconographies of the Renaissance.

19:01.580 --> 19:10.580
So now we have reclaimed what seems to be the most moving aspect as it were of A.B. Varbog

19:10.580 --> 19:14.940
and its finding its fruition in the kinds of work which we have seen done amongst the

19:14.940 --> 19:19.060
cognitive neuroscience and with the development of the neuroscience of emotion movement and

19:19.060 --> 19:20.060
so on.

19:20.060 --> 19:22.060
So I think we have a lot of people who are going to be able to move ahead in this direction.

19:22.060 --> 19:28.260
But I just thought that that historical background would be useful.

19:28.260 --> 19:33.460
Adding perhaps another issue to this question of the historical background more generally

19:33.460 --> 19:38.860
as regards German culture in the 19th century.

19:38.860 --> 19:47.740
Victoria, you told us about this figure, a special figure of Varbog as a possible bridge

19:47.740 --> 19:54.860
between natural sciences and humanities.

19:54.860 --> 20:01.660
We know that the German philosophical and epistemological discourse was responsible

20:01.660 --> 20:08.780
for the division, the terminus technique was between Geistes Wiesenshaften on one side

20:08.780 --> 20:13.660
and Mathur Wiesenshaften on the other side.

20:13.660 --> 20:24.540
For the rest it was not unfrequent that students and scholars training in one field took courses

20:24.540 --> 20:26.700
in the other.

20:26.700 --> 20:34.780
Varbog himself is an example, an emblematic example because he was trained as an art historian

20:34.780 --> 20:42.060
but in the 90s he went to Berlin to attend courses in medicine, at the Faculty of Medicine.

20:42.060 --> 20:50.020
There is studied neurology and you find in the fragments on the psychology of expression

20:50.020 --> 20:56.980
very interesting sketches and drawings on the structure of the nerves, on the problem

20:56.980 --> 21:08.300
of the reflex and there are drawings about the relationship between stimulus and response.

21:08.300 --> 21:16.660
And then he read neurologists like Evelle Herring and the very important lecture in 1870 on

21:16.660 --> 21:24.860
memory as organized matter and then among his sources there was Richard Zehmon, a zoologist

21:24.860 --> 21:33.580
and neurologist as well who gave him the terminus technique was Mime N. Graham.

21:33.580 --> 21:43.860
So he was really imbued with this literature and I think that just taking one of the most

21:43.860 --> 21:53.300
famous concepts in Varbog's discourse, Sophros Zune, the ancient Greek world that it translates

21:53.300 --> 21:55.300
with based on and height.

21:55.300 --> 22:07.100
I'm not sure what an English possible translation would be, caution, prudence, being wise, not

22:07.100 --> 22:09.100
being impulsive.

22:09.100 --> 22:16.540
There you find this idea of distance as interval, pose as crucial.

22:16.540 --> 22:21.140
It was not only a question of symbolic distance.

22:21.140 --> 22:27.900
The one that he discusses, for example, in the certain ritual lecture that modern technology

22:27.900 --> 22:37.700
destroys the distance that magic and art had instituted between man and world.

22:37.700 --> 22:45.460
It speaks also of distance in a neurological way, meaning the distance between the stimulus,

22:45.460 --> 22:56.500
the response and the human being has the creature that can procrastinate, that can introduce

22:56.500 --> 23:05.780
mediation, a postponement, a creature that is not obliged to immediately respond to the

23:05.780 --> 23:13.580
stimulus but that can respond and Zehmon was very important to him in this context in a

23:13.580 --> 23:17.300
procrastinated way, in a delayed way.

23:17.300 --> 23:28.620
Image plays in this frame, I think, a very fundamental role because image has a biological

23:28.620 --> 23:39.700
meaning in this biological utility in helping men in negotiating between stimulus and response,

23:39.700 --> 23:47.140
corresponding the response, even for centuries, even for thousands of years.

23:47.140 --> 23:54.700
And so this idea was thistchen round, bank round, the space in between, the space for

23:54.700 --> 24:01.980
thought, the space for memory and that's around, all terms that Warburg evokes as a

24:01.980 --> 24:05.740
constellation around the Sophros unit term.

24:05.740 --> 24:12.020
I think they can also be usefully investigated from a neurological perspective, rooted in

24:12.020 --> 24:16.860
those young years of studies in Berlin.

24:16.860 --> 24:30.020
I wonder if I could pose a question as I've been listening to this, that I'm still trying

24:30.020 --> 24:33.580
to get my head around.

24:33.580 --> 24:41.980
Which is on the one hand, there are cultural theories of which I am relatively ignorant

24:41.980 --> 24:51.380
of and on the other hand, there is psychoanalysis of which I am relatively ignorant and a sconst

24:51.380 --> 24:52.380
in between.

24:52.380 --> 24:59.620
Is that like a double negative?

24:59.620 --> 25:09.460
And then there's neuroscience of which I have some knowledge and in part, I'm trying to

25:09.460 --> 25:12.780
figure out what the relationships of these things are.

25:12.780 --> 25:19.460
And on the one hand, you can think of cultural theories as something that is an emergent

25:19.460 --> 25:25.060
property of a whole lot of things but can't be reduced to what one individual person or

25:25.060 --> 25:28.740
what one individual brain is doing.

25:28.740 --> 25:38.140
And at the other end, at least my medical school knowledge of psychoanalysis is a deep dive

25:38.140 --> 25:44.860
into the individual at the level of the content of what they're talking about, what they're

25:44.860 --> 25:50.500
thinking about, what they're dreaming about, what they associate, so on and so forth.

25:50.500 --> 25:54.900
But neuroscience in some way seems to be somewhere in between, at least the way it's typically

25:54.900 --> 26:02.500
practiced which is on the one hand, our methods are driven to try to generalize, it's the

26:02.500 --> 26:08.020
inherent nature of much of empirical research is you want to get generalizable principles

26:08.020 --> 26:13.860
but not typically so generalizable that they are applicable to cultural theories.

26:13.860 --> 26:20.220
And the very inherent nature of generalizing is that we typically tend to be less interested

26:20.220 --> 26:21.860
in the individual.

26:21.860 --> 26:27.980
The individual becomes one exemplar of a general principle that we're trying to derive.

26:27.980 --> 26:35.180
And psychoanalysis on the one hand seems to be, seems to drill down at the individual

26:35.180 --> 26:40.740
and the content of the experience of the individual that we typically try to do away with in most

26:40.740 --> 26:43.580
neuroscience studies.

26:43.580 --> 26:49.620
But our generalization doesn't generalize to the point of having at least in a transparent

26:49.620 --> 26:54.780
way making contact with cultural notions.

26:54.780 --> 27:01.940
And I'm just curious what people think about, are these tensions that are inherent in the

27:01.940 --> 27:08.340
disciplines or are these just historical tensions that have to be traversed and settings like

27:08.340 --> 27:10.780
this might help in that regard?

27:10.780 --> 27:20.700
It's my turn to answer.

27:20.700 --> 27:23.700
Thank you very much.

27:23.700 --> 27:25.500
It's a small issue.

27:25.500 --> 27:36.660
Actually, one of the things that was fascinating, the most about Warburg, is that he's expressing,

27:36.660 --> 27:41.540
I'm not sure for the first time in the history of thought because we can always go back to

27:41.540 --> 27:48.940
the Greeks for almost everything, but exactly the tension between subjective and objective

27:48.940 --> 27:53.780
individuality and socially.

27:53.780 --> 28:07.860
I think one of the most striking things that make us what we are, this tension of being

28:07.860 --> 28:17.260
