So there's a classic relatively rare but classic neurologic syndrome called the Alien Hand

01:25:25.680 --> 01:25:26.920
Syndrome.

01:25:26.920 --> 01:25:35.880
And this is one in which we've done one of the few experimental studies of such a patient.

01:25:35.880 --> 01:25:40.080
So let me just describe it for people who are not aware of this.

01:25:40.080 --> 01:25:45.880
This is a situation where someone's hand, it's typically on one side, seems to be

01:25:45.880 --> 01:25:53.640
to perform behaviors that seem complex but over which they have no control.

01:25:53.640 --> 01:25:59.720
And so the particular man that we studied about seven or eight years ago, I mean he would

01:25:59.720 --> 01:26:03.360
come in and he'd sit down and he'd sit down on his hand because he didn't want his hand

01:26:03.360 --> 01:26:06.040
doing things that he had no control over.

01:26:06.040 --> 01:26:10.960
These kinds of, or he'd grab a magazine or a cup and hold this because as long as his

01:26:10.960 --> 01:26:13.360
hand was occupied it wouldn't do things.

01:26:13.360 --> 01:26:20.760
But what are the kinds of things it does is that it will, he'll walk by a light switch

01:26:20.760 --> 01:26:24.560
and his hand will reach up and start doing this turning on and off on and off on and

01:26:24.560 --> 01:26:27.080
off the lights.

01:26:27.080 --> 01:26:32.680
And there are a variety of these kinds of behaviors and what we, and his lesion, just

01:26:32.680 --> 01:26:38.200
so you know the part of his brain that was damaged is the medial part of the frontal

01:26:38.200 --> 01:26:39.200
lobe, right?

01:26:39.200 --> 01:26:43.880
The classic location for this kind of phenomenon.

01:26:43.880 --> 01:26:51.400
What we were able to show is the conditions in which this happens are two.

01:26:51.400 --> 01:27:01.680
One is that the control over affordances that most of us normally have, he didn't have.

01:27:01.680 --> 01:27:02.840
And what do I mean by that?

01:27:02.840 --> 01:27:11.520
Which is if you see a cup with a handle there is a kind of affordance that makes you want

01:27:11.520 --> 01:27:12.880
to grasp it, right?

01:27:12.880 --> 01:27:18.920
And it's likely that the mirror neuron system is in fact involved in that kind of experience.

01:27:18.920 --> 01:27:21.080
Most of us can choose to do this or not.

01:27:21.080 --> 01:27:27.320
And it should be clear that most of us, our motor systems operate below consciousness most

01:27:27.320 --> 01:27:28.480
of the time, right?

01:27:28.480 --> 01:27:32.160
Where usually you think about every time you drive to work or you walk to work you are

01:27:32.160 --> 01:27:35.080
not really aware of all the little decisions you're making.

01:27:35.080 --> 01:27:40.720
We largely respond to things in the environment with our motor systems and that's what this

01:27:40.720 --> 01:27:47.760
person was doing but unlike the rest of us is not able to control it.

01:27:47.760 --> 01:27:51.480
The second piece of this is he was exquisitely aware of this.

01:27:51.480 --> 01:27:55.320
So if you have damage bilaterally you get something called utilization behavior where

01:27:55.320 --> 01:27:58.840
people do this but they're completely apathetic about it.

01:27:58.840 --> 01:28:04.520
So he had this monitoring system over his own motor behavior.

01:28:04.520 --> 01:28:09.800
At the same time he didn't have control over one side and then this creates this sense

01:28:09.800 --> 01:28:14.880
that this limb is doing something of which he has no control over, right?

01:28:14.880 --> 01:28:18.040
It's completely responsive to the environment.

01:28:18.040 --> 01:28:21.920
